					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Nice breakdown, tepples. If you needed the whole stack, you could save/restore it to/from temporary area at 15 clocks per byte (8 to save it and 7 to restore it). If a normal 64 byte stack area were being used and the whole 256 bytes were needed for a quick buffer copy, swapping these 64 bytes out and back in would take 960 cycles total. This of course would be done in non-cycle-critical code.
<br />
<br />Heh, a mapper which allowed changing the stack and/or zero page would be neat (like on the 65816 in the SNES).</div>

